mework for Intercultural Citizenship -- tAppendix 4 Autobiography of Intercultural Encounters85 -- tNotes -- tReferences0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis collection of essays and reflections starts from an analysis of the purposes of foreign language teaching and argues that this should include educational objectives which are ultimately similar to those of education for citizenship. It does so by a journey through reflections on what is possible and desirable in the classroom and how language teaching has a specific role in education systems which have long had, and often still have, the purpose of encouraging young people to identify with the nation-state. Foreign language education can break through this framework to introduce a critical internationalism. In a ‘globalised’ and ‘internationalised’ world, the importance of identification with people beyond the national borders is crucial. Combined with education for citizenship, foreign language education can offer an education for ‘intercultural citizenship’.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aIntercultural communicationxStudy and teaching. 0aLanguages, ModernxStudy and teaching. 0aMulticultural education. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Study & Teaching.2bisacsh  aForeign Language Teaching.  acitizenship education.  aintercultural learning.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertMultiLingual Matters Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066313608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertMultiLingual Matters eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014z978311060671340uhttps://doi.org/10.21832/978184769080740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781847690807423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781847690807/original  a978-3-11-060671-3  MultiLingu